        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent.</placeName>
                    <date>March 31<hi rend="superscript">st</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you exceedingly &amp; very sincerely for all the trouble you have taken.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I really had no thought to give so much trouble.— You indeed in your note show yourself well up to the current literature— If <hi rend="underline">you</hi> cannot find Godron, it is hopeless. It is not known by booksellers at Paris, or here by Williams &amp; Norgate<ref target="#foot.f2"/> or at Kew by Hooker &amp; Bentham.—</p>
<p>I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. certainly have been very glad to have known what it is about. But I must give it up.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> How useful a parallel book to Agassiz &amp; Stricklands Zoolog Bibliography<ref target="#foot.f4"/> would be in Botany!.— Thank you, also, for telling me where to find Hornschuch, though your remarks take off much of my wish to see it.<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>Thank you very much for the extremely kind manner in which you offer me assistance: I do not know that I shall require it; but if I do, I will not scruple to intrude on your kindness.</p>
<p>Pray believe me | My dear Sir | Your’s truly obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.2 March] <hi rend="italic">after omitted point</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.2 give] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘cost’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">2.2 Zoolog] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n4">2.3 you,] <hi rend="italic">before omitted comma</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n5">2.4 Hornschuch,] <hi rend="italic">altered from</hi> ‘Hornscuch’</note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1648.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Arthur Henfrey, 17 March [1855]</ref>. CD had been searching for a copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2887.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Godron 1848–9</ref> since early March (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1638.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, [before 7 March 1855]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1643.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 7 March [1855]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Booksellers specialising in foreign medical and scientific literature.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD recorded the title of Godron’s paper (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2887.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Godron 1848–9</ref>) in his list of books to be read and at some stage marked it as having been read (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4, Appendix IV, *128: 177). However, it is likely that he did not succeed in locating a copy until after writing <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref> and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>, for it is not cited in either of these works. CD acquired a copy of Godron’s expanded version of the earlier work (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2890.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Godron 1859</ref>), which is now in the Darwin Library–CUL.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The <hi rend="italic">Bibliographia zoologiæ et geologiæ</hi>, compiled by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_43.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Louis Agassiz</ref> and expanded by Hugh Strickland (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_56.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Agassiz 1848–54</ref>). CD had prepared a list of his publications for inclusion (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1215.xml" resp="#automat">letter to H. E. Strickland, 29 January [1849]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3869.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hornschuch 1848</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1648.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Arthur Henfrey, 17 March [1855]</ref>). In spite of his reservations, CD cited Friedrich Hornschuch twice in <hi rend="italic">Natural</hi> <hi rend="italic">selection</hi>, pp. 102, 127.</note>
        </div>        
            
